@node VCH "Video Cassette Header"
@{i}By Chris Young 1997@{ui}

This is a video headering sort of program, like what you get at the start of pre-recorded videos.
Basically, it'll ask you some questions, and then a screen like this will appear (which you should promptly record onto your video)
@{bg text}@{fg shine}
TAPE 01 E180 SP  @{bg back}@{fg text} TAPE NUMBER LENGTH MODE@{bg text}@{fg shine}
00:00:00         @{bg back}@{fg text} COUNTER POSITION@{bg text}@{fg shine}
21/11/97 21:00   @{bg back}@{fg text} DATE TIME@{bg text}@{fg shine}
FILM (C) CH 5    @{bg back}@{fg text} PROG TYPE (RATING) CHANNEL@{bg text}@{fg shine}
01 EXAMPLE ONLY! @{bg back}@{fg text} PROG NUMBER PROG NAME

If you opt not to type in programme info (ie. you just want a standard header, then it'll look more like this:
@{bg text}@{fg shine}
TAPE 01 E180 SP  @{bg back}@{fg text} TAPE NUMBER LENGTH MODE@{bg text}@{fg shine}
00:00:00         @{bg back}@{fg text} COUNTER POSITION@{bg text}@{fg shine}
21/11/97 21:00   @{bg back}@{fg text} DATE TIME

Oh, and this requires the ttext-std-??? fonts used with some BBC emulator
@endnode

@node MSDOSEM "MS-DOS Prompt Emulator"
@{i}Based on the Windows 95 DOS Prompt@{ui}

Type 'EXIT' to return to Workbench.  That's it really.

MS-DOS is a trademark of Microsoft Corp.
@endnode

@node DHRacer "Downhill Racer (or The Skiing On That Thin Crust Known As Reality Simulator)"
@{i}Based on an original program in that Osbourne book I've mentioned elsewhere in this guide
This is an enhanced version by Chris Young and Phillip Lake 1997@{ui}

Basically, you're skiing down a ski slope thing.  The trees mark the precipice.  You can resize the window to suit your mood or skill level, and the run will move over and utilise the space provided.  Please note that the game slows down if you make the window taller, and speeds up if you make it smaller.
The graphics are courtesy of my new improved spectrum.font, so if you just get strange or no characters, make sure you copy over the new speccy font.

Controls: Either use the keys , and . (comma and full stop) or...
                 use the mouse, by holding down the left mouse button and frantically pushing it left and right in the vain hope that you will stay on the run/the mouse will actually work for once.
@endnode

@node CATS "Create A Teletext Service"
@{u}Create A Teletext Service/CATS Editor@{uu}
@{i}by Chris Young, based on my earlier teletext-style programs@{ui}

Read the 'on-line help', in the form of the automatically-loaded help file which will automatically appear upon loading CATS.

Basic instructions:

press keys 0-9 to enter the three digit page number
           F1-F4 for fastext links red-cyan
           Space to load another database (must be in same drawer as CATS)
           Ctrl-C to quit

CATS Editor

enter a database name, and answer any questions that follow. click the mouse button (left) and then tap in the three-digit page number...

Click on Pxxx for a new page
         LOAD to load the page
         SAVE to save it
         @{bg shine}*@{bg back} etc to change the background colour
         @{bg shadow}@{fg shine}*@{fg shadow}@{bg back} etc to change the foreground colour
         anywhere to set colour
                  then type
@endnode

@node 5text "Channel 5 pre-broadcast teletext service"
This is a copy (although a slightly lower resolution one) of Channel 5's pre-broadcast teletext service.  It includes the legendary 'secret page' 515 which appeared for just a couple of hours on the Thursday before they started broadcasting properly.  It also has secret page 598, which is a teletext 'magic eye' picture.
Load it up and tap in some numbers.  You may be required to give the weekday.  If so, enter it in three-character format.
@endnode

@node Whittle "Whittle"
It's time to be Whittled!  And here's the man to Whittle you down... Tiiiiiiiiiiiiiiimmmm Viiiine

"Welcome to Whittle, with me, your host, Tim Vine"

Actually, contrary to popular belief (ie. the lies we made up and spread through the YS App, which is so phonomenally popular that it started everyone doing Tim Vine impressions (by saying "It's me, your host, Tim Vine") and making their own Channel 5 Tim Vine-style quiz shows, with help from the Tim Vine DIY Quiz Show Page.  And phoning up Future Publishing asking for back issues of YS.

NOTE: In the Amiga version, you use the keys r g y c to correspond to the fastext red, green, yellow and cyan links.

@{u}The Listing (tm)@{uu}

Int (Ran#×4)+1 -> Z
"ARE YOU READYTO BE"
"WHITTLED?"/
"WHITTLE AWAY!"/
"YOU COULD WIN250 QUID OR  500!"
Z=1 => "CANCEL THE   MORTGAGE!"/
Z=2 => "DID YOU HOLD UP A BANK?"/
