@node VKettley "Virtual Kettley: The John Kettley Simulator"
@{u}Virtual Kettley@{uu}
@{i}By Chris Young 1996, from an idea by PC Zone@{ui}
(requires ARexx to be active)

According to Duncan MacDonald (of @{"ALS" link ALS} fame), John Kettley always trys to link the weather in with the news.  He also wrote that he tried to create a program which generates what John Kettley will say (it didn't work, though).  This is, in fact, what this program is based on: Type in the last news item (for example, "the stealth bomber", which is the last item at the time of writing) and John Kettley's opening line will be displayed.
@endnode

@node VDarling "Virtual Darling: The David Darling Simulator"
@{u}Virtual Darling@{uu}
@{i}By Chris Young 1996, from the comments you used to get on Codemasters' budget Spectrum games and the fact Your Sinclair kept commenting on these comments.@{ui}
(requires ARexx)

David Darling, one of the Darling brothers (ie. the original Codemasters), always put a comment on their games (or, at least, the Spectrum budget games).  This comment was, "It's absolutely brilliant!".  OK, there's nothing wrong with that: most of their games were.  But @{i}Your Sinclair@{ui} brought this up on the letters page at least a couple of times.  Once someone wrote in claiming a trainspotter because YS had said the latest Dizzy game was "Fantasy World Dizzy", when YS had called it "Fantasy Land Dizzy".  Obviously, they phoned David Darling to find out what it was actually called.  The result?  Absolutely Brilliant. Excellent Dizzy. (or something like that)

Upon running, you have to type in a question for Virtual David, and read the result.
@endnode


@node Maths "Maths Test"
@{u}0 out of 10 Maths@{uu}
@{i}By Chris Young, based on some PC demo maths KS1 IQ test thing, or something@{ui}

After loading (ARexx! Arexx! Arexx!), you get asked some maths questions.  After answering them all, you will be informed how many you got right.  Well, that's it really.

@{"Casio Version" link CMaths}
@endnode


@node BTMan "Bush Tucker Man: The Game"
@{u}Bush Tucker Man@{uu}
@{i}By Chris Young/Unsatisfactory Software 1996@{ui}

This game is based on the TV programme of the same name: you guide Bush Tucker Man across the Australian Outback, by means of the keys described below.  Basically this is a "Frogger" clone - avoid the crocs in the river (instead of cars on a road) and the moving bushes.  Jump onto the backs of birds flying along a ditch (instead of logs on a river.  Although frogs can swim, can't they?  So why do they need to use logs?) and over to the asterisks (*).  One Bush Tucker Man per asterisk.  After "collecting the set", the game is over.

Other things to note:
On the menu screen, you can use + (or =) and - to adjust the game speed.  This goes from virtually stopped to as fast as your computer can go (actually, a bit slower than that because HiSoft BASIC programs tend to have a low priority.  Or seem to have, anyway).  It is possible that "as fast as possible" is actually the same speed as "very fast" - it depends on the speed of your machine and whether it can go any faster than "very fast".
This speed only determines the updates/checks on crocs and things.  On "as slow as possible" (or whatever it's called), you can pass through all the crocs and across the ditch without dying!

Your score, displayed at the bottom with "spare" processor time, is calculated on time taken and difficulty level (speed).  If you die straight away on "a. f. a. p.", you may get more score than completing (almost) stop.

Controls:      8
               @{fg highlight}^@{fg text}
             4@{fg highlight}< >@{fg text}6
               @{fg highlight}v@{fg text}
               2
               
@{"Casio Version" link Bush}

PS. You may be interested to know I completed this on Saturday.
@endnode

@node Tips "Chris' Top Money Saving Tips"
@{u}Chris' Top Money-Saving Tips@{uu}
@{b}I accept NO responsibility for any damage to equipment etc. through use of these handy money-saving tips.@{ub}

@{i}Number One@{ui}

Why waste money on expensive CD-ROM burners and gold discs?  Just pop down the local photocopying bureau with your mates CD.  Simply photocopy the shiny side (don't change the size) onto a sheet of A4.  Using sticky-backed plastic and an empty cereal box, you can attach the photocopy onto the cardboard.  Take a pair of scissors and carefully cut round the photocopied disc.  With a craft knife (get an adult to help you), cut out the hole in the middle of the disc.  You have now made an exact copy of the original CD.  Put it in your CD-ROM drive, and try it out.  It'll work (honest).  But, first, run back to the photocopier you used and pick up your mate's CD - you left it there, didn't you?

@{i}Money-making tip@{ui}

Pretend to be abducted by aliens, re-incarnated, or something (no-one can prove you weren't) and sell your story to The Sun (or Fortean TV) for pots of cash.
@endnode

