 6. (4)  92˛
 7. (9)  17
 8. (RE) Sqr(2)
 9. (10) 27
10. (57) 1

32, which has been hovering around the top for a few months now, has finally made it to number 1.  There's a new entry a number 3, with the number of kilobytes in 4 megabytes.  14 million, the odds of winning the lottery, is down to number 4 when everyone realised that they hadn't won yet.  1 has shot up the chart to tenth place, knocking pi out of its spot, after sitting down at position 57 for the last few weeks.  Those of you wondering where e is, should be aware that it is actually not even in the top 500.
@endnode

